defaultPe
defaultrsonalised services for patien
defaultts (Personalised health budgets;
default Care planning)
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultFollowing recent pilot
defaulting
default, the Department of Health
default 
defaulthas 
defaultannounced the initial roll out of personal health budgets
default (PHBs)
default in England
default, which aim to give people with long term conditions greater choice, flexibility and control over their health services and the support they receive.
default 
defaultFrom
default 
defaultApril 2014
default,
default 
defaultall people receiving 
defaultNHS Continuing Healthcare will have the right to ask for a personal health budget
default, whilst clinical commissioning g
defaultroups and NHS England will be able to offer PHBs more widely
default.
default&#xa0;
defaultHowever, as arthritis and other musculoskeletal conditions were not the 
defaultdedicated 
defaultfocus of any of the pilot sites, Arthritis Research UK undertook work to ensure the perspectives of people with these conditions was heard.
default&#xa0;
defaultOur August 2012 report 
defaultPersonal Health Budgets 
defaultpresents the findings of our survey, workshop and policy seminar,
default 
defaultand 
defaultincludes five recommendations 
defaultfor action as PHBs become more widely available on the NHS:
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultFor many musculoskeletal conditions, 
defaultsuch as
default back pain and osteoarthritis, effective day-to-day self-management can make a substantial difference to the overall impact of the condition on a person’s health and wellbeing.
default We believe that a systematic approach to care planning can benefit people with arthritis and other musculoskeletal conditions, and that care planning offers important opportunities to deliver improvements in their care. 
default&#xa0;
defaultAlthough the term 
default‘
defaultcare planning
default’
default is not used directly, NICE clinical guidelines recommend the development of a management plan for people with osteoarthritis, and 
defaultthe offer of an annual review to people with rheumatoid arthritis
default.
default,
default However, recent 
defaultsurvey 
defaultestimates suggest that only 18% of people with osteoarthritis
default and 20% of people with rheumatoid arthritis
default have an agreed care plan.
default,
default&#xa0;
defaultA welcome recent development is the introduction of rheumatoid arthritis 
defaultinto the
default Quality and Outcom
defaultes Framework (QOF) for 2013/14. In addition to maintaining a register of people with rheumatoid arthritis, GPs will
default be incentivised to 
defaultensure patients have an annual face-to-face review
default,
default 
defaultwhich
default may
default provide an 
defaultimportant
default opportunity to systematically integrate care p
defaultlanning conversations for people with rheumatoid arthritis
default. 
defaultThis 
defaultis the first time that measures
default for people with rheumatoid arthritis
default have been included
default – other measures included are fracture and cardiovascular risk assessments.
default 
defaultWhile this new addition to the QOF represents a valuable opportunity to improve the management of rheumatoid arthritis, it is also important to ensure there is effective communication between primary and secondary care.
default&#xa0;
defaultMusculoskeletal conditions are generally long term conditions which often fluctuate over time. For example, rheumatoid arthritis is often categorised by periods of flare-up interspersed with periods in which symptoms lessen.
default This is something that the care planning process should take into account. 
defaultMuch can be learnt from extending the model of high quality proactive care that has driven 
defaultimprovement in diabetes –
default particularly
default the Year of Care programme which focused on the practicalities of the delivery of care planning in primary care settings.
default 
default&#xa0;
defaultC
defaultare planning 
defaultshould not be
default an isolated exercise and records and plans 
defaultshould be
default described in language which is accessible and familiar to the person involved
default, along with clear communication about how the process works
default.
default 
defaultWe welcome the development that has already been made in this area, with the recently revised NHS Constitution now including the pledge ‘to involve you in discussions about planning your care and to offer you a written record of what is agreed if you want one’.
default 
default&#xa0;
defaultOver time, we 
defaultwish
default to see care planning embedded across the NHS for people with long term conditions. In particular, we ask that NHS England meets the commitment set out in its mandate that ‘everyone with a long term condition … will be offered a personalised care plan that reflects their preferences and agreed decisions’.
